<subSubSection pageId="148" pageNumber="149" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="148.[151,1437,607,1208]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,751,776]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Female 
<taxonomicName box="[411,568,752,776]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="novascotiae">
<emphasis box="[411,426,753,776]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[441,568,753,776]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">novascotiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognised by the following diagnostic combination: head wide (length/ width ratio = 
<number box="[296,407,788,812]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="0.955" valueMax="0.96" valueMin="0.95">0.95–0.96</number>
), clypeus strongly protruding below suborbital tangent, mesoscutal punctures sparse throughout, mesepisternum rugulose, propodeum with dorsolateral slope rugulose (
<figureCitation box="[916,995,823,847]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="23.[151,244,1344,1365]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,698,1334]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,698,1334]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 27. Dorsolateral slope of propodeum (A) L. lineatulum, (B) L. smilacinae. (From Gibbs 2010 b)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1049649/files/figure.png" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
Fig. 
<number box="[966,995,823,847]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
B), and metasomal terga blackish brown. They are most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[415,557,860,884]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineatulum">
<emphasis box="[415,430,861,884]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[443,557,860,884]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">lineatulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has head wider (length/width ratio = 
<number box="[1031,1143,860,884]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="0.925" valueMax="0.93" valueMin="0.92">0.92–0.93</number>
), propodeum with dorsolateral slope smooth (
<figureCitation box="[353,430,895,919]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="23.[151,244,1344,1365]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,698,1334]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,698,1334]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 27. Dorsolateral slope of propodeum (A) L. lineatulum, (B) L. smilacinae. (From Gibbs 2010 b)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1049649/files/figure.png" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
Fig. 
<number box="[402,430,895,919]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
A), and metasomal terga with metallic reflections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="148.[151,1437,607,1208]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
<collectingCountry box="[199,254,932,956]" name="Malta" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Male</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName box="[266,426,933,956]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="novascotiae">
<emphasis box="[266,281,933,956]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[299,426,933,956]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">novascotiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognised by the following diagnostic combination: mesoscutal punctures sparse throughout, mesepisternum rugulose, and metasomal sterna with subappressed plumose hairs limited to apicolateral portions of S 
<number box="[252,265,1004,1028]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="3.0">3</number>
and lateral portions of S 
<number box="[524,539,1004,1028]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="4.0">4</number>
–S 
<number box="[570,583,1004,1028]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="5.0">5</number>
. They are similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[799,940,1004,1028]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineatulum">
<emphasis box="[799,814,1005,1028]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[826,940,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">lineatulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has dense plumose hairs on S 
<number box="[1335,1349,1004,1028]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
–S 
<number box="[1377,1391,1004,1028]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="4.0">4</number>
and S 
<number box="[166,180,1040,1064]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" value="5.0">5</number>
laterally. 
<taxonomicName box="[283,534,1040,1064]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="achilleae">
<emphasis box="[283,534,1040,1064]" italics="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Lasioglossum achilleae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar but has a shorter head and sparse punctation on metasomal terga.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="148.[151,1437,607,1208]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,279,1076,1100]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Range.</emphasis>
Nova 
